MARKET REGIME CLASSIFICATION
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Before performing top-down analysis, classify the current market regime.
Use the 4H and 1H charts as primary reference.

REGIME 1 : TRENDING
Conditions:
• EMA 50 clearly above/below EMA 200 with expanding gap
• Price making higher highs + higher lows (bullish) or lower highs + lower lows (bearish)
• ADX > 25 (if available) or clear impulse-pullback-impulse structure
• ATR stable or slightly expanding

Trading Rules (Trending):
→ Trade WITH the trend only (no counter-trend)
→ Enter on pullbacks to EMA 50 or unmitigated OBs
→ Hidden Divergence = best entry signal (continuation)
→ Standard R:R 1:3, can extend TP3 to 1:5+

REGIME 2 : RANGING
Conditions:
• EMA 50 ≈ EMA 200 (flat or intertwined)
• Price oscillating between defined fractal high and fractal low
• Swing highs and lows overlapping — no clear structure progression
• ATR contracting or flat

Trading Rules (Ranging):
→ Trade from range extremes ONLY (buy at range low, sell at range high)
→ Reduce R:R target to 1:2 (accept smaller moves)
→ Regular Divergence at range boundaries = best signal
→ Reduce position size to 0.75% risk
→ Expect false breakouts — wait for candle CLOSE beyond range before breakout entry
→ No Tier-3 patterns — only Tier-1 at range extremes

REGIME 3 : VOLATILE / EVENT-DRIVEN
Conditions:
• ATR > 2× its 20-period average
• Sharp, impulsive moves with large candle bodies
• Often triggered by news, liquidation cascades, or black swan events
• EMA 50 and EMA 200 may be breached rapidly

Trading Rules (Volatile):
→ Reduce position size to 0.5% risk
→ Widen SL by 1.5× normal ATR-based distance
→ Only trade AFTER the initial spike settles (wait for a range to form post-spike)
→ Liquidity sweep + rejection = best setup in this regime
→ Minimum R:R remains 1:3 but expect wider stops and larger targets
→ If unsure → ⚪ WAIT. Capital preservation is priority.

